                    <foaf:Person>
                        <foaf:surname>Weber</foaf:surname>
                        <foaf:givenName>Roberto</foaf:givenName>
                    </foaf:Person>
                </rdf:li>
                <rdf:li>
                    <foaf:Person>
                        <foaf:surname>Zubrickas</foaf:surname>
                        <foaf:givenName>Robertas</foaf:givenName>
                    </foaf:Person>
                </rdf:li>
            </rdf:Seq>
        </bib:authors>
        <link:link rdf:resource="#item_237"/>
        <dc:title>On Altruism and Remittances</dc:title>
        <dcterms:abstract>We provide a direct test of the impact of altruism on remittances. From a sample of 105 male migrant workers from Kerala, India working in Qatar, we elicit the propensity to share with others from their responses in a dictator game, and use it as a proxy for altruism. When the entire sample is considered, we ﬁnd that only migrants’ income robustly explains remittances. Altruism does not seem to matter. However, we document a strong positive relationship between altruism and remittances for those migrants that report a loan obligation back home, which is nearly half the sample. We explain the role of loan obligations with a standard remittance model, extended with reference-dependent preferences.</dcterms:abstract>
        <z:language>en</z:language>
        <z:libraryCatalog>Zotero</z:libraryCatalog>
    </bib:Article>
